input.source:
#### Guide

Welcome to quantlib.js notebook

This is a light weight `jupyter notebook` like web app for `interactive computation`, it's hosted on `github page`, after loading, it works offline.

output.content:
Guide

Welcome to quantlib.js notebook

This is a light weight jupyter notebook like web app for interactive computation, it's hosted on github page, after loading, it works offline.

input.source: ##### Notebook Actions from top navbar: * click or to lock/unlock notebook, when notebook is locked, cells can't be edited, run or removed * click button to insert a new cell after selected cell * click to run selected cell * click run all cells above selected cell * click run selected cell and all cells below * click button to run entire notebook * click button to clear all output, show all editors * click to clear selected cell output and show editor

output.content:
Notebook Actions

from top navbar:

  • click or to lock/unlock notebook, when notebook is locked, cells can't be edited, run or removed
  • click button to insert a new cell after selected cell
  • click to run selected cell
  • click run all cells above selected cell
  • click run selected cell and all cells below
  • click button to run entire notebook
  • click button to clear all output, show all editors
  • click to clear selected cell output and show editor

input.source: ##### Cell Actions * hover/click/tap cell: * click or to toggle cell type, it's either `code` or `markdown` * click to insert a new cell below * click to run a cell * click to move a cell up * click to delete a cell * click to move a cell down * double click/tap cell to show/hide editor

input.source: ##### Datebase & File I/O We added database functions, you can now save notebook to browser `indexeddb` * click to open manage notebooks dialog, from which you can * select and load notebook saved in database * delete notebook from database * click to open save notebook dialog, from which you can * save current working notebook to database * download notebook file to disk * drag notebook json file to this page to load it (open from file dialog removed) * notebook loaded from disk can be saved to database

output.content:
Datebase & File I/O

We added database functions, you can now save notebook to browser indexeddb

  • click to open manage notebooks dialog, from which you can
    • select and load notebook saved in database
    • delete notebook from database
  • click to open save notebook dialog, from which you can
    • save current working notebook to database
    • download notebook file to disk
  • drag notebook json file to this page to load it (open from file dialog removed)
    • notebook loaded from disk can be saved to database

input.source:
##### Markdown with LaTex

We use 

* [marked](https://github.com/markedjs/marked) to render [GitHub Flavored Markdown](https://github.github.com/gfm/)

* [katex](https://katex.org/) to render `LaTex`, example: $ c = \pm\sqrt{a^2 + b^2} $ (put latex inside `$$ ... $$ ` for display mode, `$ ... $` for inline mode); check out [Supported Functions](https://katex.org/docs/supported.html), [Support Table](https://katex.org/docs/support_table.html)

More Markdown tutorial can be found [here](/notebook/#markdown/tutorial.json)

More Latex tutorial can be found [here](/notebook/#latex/tutorial.json)

output.content:
Markdown with LaTex

We use

  • marked to render GitHub Flavored Markdown

  • katex to render LaTex, example: c=±a2+b2 c = \pm\sqrt{a^2 + b^2} c=±a2+b2​ (put latex inside $$ ... $$ for display mode, $ ... $ for inline mode); check out Supported Functions, Support Table

More Markdown tutorial can be found here

More Latex tutorial can be found here

LaTex protection

LaTeX content may contain text that could be interpreted as Markdown, e.g., $ {a}_{1} {a}_{2} $

Those are protected and rendered as LaTeX a1a2 {a}_{1} {a}_{2} a1​a2​ instead of Markdown {a}{1} {a}{2}

input.source:
##### Code Execution

In old version, we load all libraries up front, this makes notebook intialization slow.

we've changed this behavior, initially no libraries used to do calculation will be loaded.

Instead, we added `require` API for user to load libs required.

Available libraries:

* quantlib
  * the main library to do quantitative finance in javascript
  
> we use to make all quantlib classes available in global context, this is changed, you have to prefix `ql.` now

* help
  * this is a big lib used to lookup quantlib API documentation, some browsers is not able to load this
* typescript
  * please refer to [JavaScript vs TypeScript](#javascript-vs-typescript)
* math
  * math.js
* sql
  * experimental sql parsing and query on indexeddb, `select` only

if required, we'll add more

input.source:
##### JavaScript vs TypeScript

> we've changed this part, UI setting removed, if user need to use `typescript`, then use `require("typescript")` API to load it. If `typescript` is loaded, we'll use `typescript`, otherwise we use `javascript`

* In most cases, `ES5` javascript code should be enough, you may loose `var` to run in `un-restricted` mode, please refer to below example
* Use `typescript` when you need `OOP` features like `inheritance`, or `ES6+` features, e.g. [Discrete Hedging](#quantlib/discretehedging.json)

output.content:
JavaScript vs TypeScript

we've changed this part, UI setting removed, if user need to use typescript, then use require("typescript") API to load it. If typescript is loaded, we'll use typescript, otherwise we use javascript

  • In most cases, ES5 javascript code should be enough, you may loose var to run in un-restricted mode, please refer to below example
  • Use typescript when you need OOP features like inheritance, or ES6+ features, e.g. Discrete Hedging

input.source:
##### Help API

type `help(class, type?, name?)` to pull API document and render in output

**warning** some browsers are not able use this feature, e.g. Safari on iOS device

parameters:

 * `class`
   * exact class name, cannot be empty
 * `type`
   * `"property"` or `"method"`
   * default is empty
     if type is empty, `help` will get comment for class
 * `name`
   * `property` or `method` name, no need to add trailing number
   * default is empty
     if `name` is empty, display all `property` or `method`

> Example removed, as some browsers not support this, will take long time to yield error message

output.content:
Help API

type help(class, type?, name?) to pull API document and render in output

warning some browsers are not able use this feature, e.g. Safari on iOS device

parameters:

  • class
    • exact class name, cannot be empty
  • type
    • "property" or "method"
    • default is empty if type is empty, help will get comment for class

    • default is empty if name is empty, display all property or method

input.source:
##### Render API
* last evaluated expression goes to cell output
  * object will be rendered as `json tree`, please see below example
  * we're planning to add more smart rendering features, so you don't need to call render api direclty
* use `print()` for primitive data type, like `number` or `string`
  * it can be called multiple times in a cell, results are appended to cell output
* use `table()` for tabular data
  * only Array of objects are supported
  * objects need to have same properties
  * uses bootstrap table class, which fills entire cell output
  * it can be called multiple times in a cell, but this might change in the future
* use `plot()` to render chart. we use [highcharts](https://www.highcharts.com) library, chart is svg format
  * svg chart will take entire cell output
  * multiple plots in a cell is not supported
  * do not use `plot` with other render API

    • it can be called multiple times in a cell, results are appended to cell output
  • use table() for tabular data
    • only Array of objects are supported
    • objects need to have same properties
    • uses bootstrap table class, which fills entire cell output
    • it can be called multiple times in a cell, but this might change in the future
  • use plot() to render chart. we use highcharts library, chart is svg format
    • svg chart will take entire cell output
    • multiple plots in a cell is not supported
    • do not use plot with other render API

input.source:
##### Plot API
 
* plot can be saved in and loaded from notebook as svg element
* when notebook is loaded, plot is `disconnected` from it's `data`, interactivity is lost, you have to re-run the cells that produce the `data`, and plot again
* when theme is changed, you have to re-run plot cell to reflect the color theme change

output.content:
Plot API

  • when notebook is loaded, plot is disconnected from it's data, interactivity is lost, you have to re-run the cells that produce the data, and plot again
  • when theme is changed, you have to re-run plot cell to reflect the color theme change
